<subsubsection xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"><title> Terms and Coefficients </title>

	<aside><title> ðŸ“Œ Note: Defining Terms </title>
		<p>
			Although, a <q>term</q> is generic way to describe a mathematical object. To avoid confusion, we will only use it as defined here.
		</p>
	</aside>

	<p>
		A differential equation is constructed from <em>terms</em>, each separated by a plus (<m>+</m>), minus (<m>-</m>), or equal (<m>=</m>) sign and is associated with the dependent variable or its derivatives. If a term does not contain a dependent variable, it is called a <term>constant term</term>. For example, the differential equation:
	</p>
	
	<men xml:id="terms-coefficients-example">
		\frac{3}{x} y^{(6)} + 5.3 y'' + x^2 (y'-4)^3 - y = \frac12\ln(x)
	</men>
	
	<p>
		contains the following terms:
	</p>
	
	<p>
		<tabular halign="center">
			<row>
				<cell><m>\ul{y^{(6)}\text{ term}}</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\ul{y''\text{ term}}</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\ul{(y'-4)^3\text{ term}}</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\ul{y\text{ term}}</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\ul{\text{constant term}}</m></cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell><m>\ds \frac{3}{x} y^{(6)}</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\ds 5.3 y''</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\ds x^2 (y'-4)^3</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\ds -y</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\ds \frac12\ln(x)</m></cell>
			</row>
		</tabular>
	</p>
	
	<p>
		Every differential equation has at least a zero constant term. For example, the equation <m>y' = -3y</m> can be rewritten as <m>y' + 3y = 0</m>, showing an implicit <m>0</m> constant term.
	</p>

	<p>
		The coefficients in a differential equation are constants or functions that multiply the dependent variable or its derivatives. These coefficients critically influence the behavior of the equation and the solution methods applicable. In the equation:
	</p>
	
	<men xml:id="coefficients-example">
		y'' - 3y' + 2y = 0,
	</men>
	
	<p>
		the coefficients are:
	</p>
	
	<p>
		<tabular halign="center">
			<row>
				<cell><m>\ul{y''\text{ coefficient}}</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\ul{y' \text{ coefficient}}</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\ul{y  \text{ coefficient}}</m></cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell><m>1</m></cell>
				<cell><m>-3</m></cell>
				<cell><m>2</m></cell>
			</row>
		</tabular>
	</p>

	<p>
		Coefficients may also be functions of the independent variable, as seen in the equation:
	</p>
	
	<men xml:id="variable-coefficients-example">
		t^2 y'' + 5t y' + 6y = \sin(t).
	</men>
	
	<p>
		Here, the coefficients are:
	</p>
	
	<p>
		<tabular halign="center">
			<row>
				<cell><m>\ul{y''\text{ coefficient}}</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\ul{y' \text{ coefficient}}</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\ul{y  \text{ coefficient}}</m></cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell><m>t^2</m></cell>
				<cell><m>5t</m></cell>
				<cell><m>6</m></cell>
			</row>
		</tabular>
	</p>

	<example xml:id="terms-and-coefficients-example">
		<statement>
			<p>
				Identify the terms and coefficients in the equation:
				<me>
					3t^2 z' - 4\cos t + \frac{z'z}{t} - 515 \sqrt{1+z^2} = -7.
				</me>
			</p>
		</statement>
		<solution>
			<p>
				The dependent variable in this equation is <m>z</m>. The <m>-4\cos t</m> and <m>-7</m> do not contain <m>z</m>, so they combine as a single constant term on the right-hand side:
				<me>
					3t^2 z' + \frac{1}{t} z'z - 515 \sqrt{1+z^2} = 4\cos t - 7.
				</me>
				The terms and coefficients are:
				<tabular halign="center">
					<row>
						<cell><m>\ul{z'\ \text{ term}}</m></cell>
						<cell><m>\ul{z'z\ \text{ term}}</m></cell>
						<cell><m>\ul{\sqrt{1+z^2}\ \text{ term}}</m></cell>
						<cell><m>\ul{\text{constant term}}</m></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><m>3t^2 z'</m></cell>
						<cell><m>\frac{1}{t} z'z</m></cell>
						<cell><m>-515 \sqrt{1+z^2}</m></cell>
						<cell><m>4\cos t - 7</m></cell>
					</row>
				</tabular>
				<tabular halign="center">
					<row>
						<cell><m>\ul{z'\ \text{ coefficient}}</m></cell>
						<cell><m>\ul{z'z\ \text{ coefficient}}</m></cell>
						<cell><m>\ul{\sqrt{1+z^2}\ \text{ coefficient}}</m></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><m>3t^2</m></cell>
						<cell><m>\frac{1}{t}</m></cell>
						<cell><m>-515</m></cell>
					</row>
				</tabular>
			</p>
		</solution>
	</example>

	<p>
		Understanding the roles of terms and coefficients will guide us in classifying and solving differential equations effectively.
	</p>

	<xi:include href="./chkpts-1-2-2-terms-coeffs.ptx" />

</subsubsection>